Title: Architecture: Azure B2C with Custom Policies for Digital ID and Authenticator app - TOTP for Power Portal using Dynamics 365 CE - TEST
Description:
Objective:
To implement Azure Active Directory B2C (Azure B2C) with custom policies for user authentication and authorization in a Power Portal. The solution will retrieve claims from Digital ID API integrated with Services Australia 

Overview:
This feature involves configuring Azure B2C, developing custom policies, integrating Services Australia Digital ID API to fetch user claims, and integrating this setup with a Power Portal that utilizes Dynamics 365 CE data.

High-Level Steps:
1. Setup Azure B2C Tenant
2. Create Custom Policies in Azure B2C
3. Develop API for Claims Retrieval from Services Australia Digital ID API or use Services Australia API [Need to find out]
4. Integrate Azure B2C with Power Portal
5. Testing and Validation
6. Deployment and Monitoring

Scenario 1: Submitting an application for a tipoff via Power Pages Portal Using Azure B2C with Email and MFA

User Journey:
  1. User Accesses Portal:
    1. John visits the Power Pages portal to apply for a tipoff.
    2. He clicks on "Submit Application."
  2. Sign-in Process:
    1. John is prompted to sign in using his email address.
    2. The portal redirects John to the Azure B2C login page.
  3. Email Verification:
    1. John enters his email address.
    2. Azure B2C sends a verification code to John’s email.
  4. Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA):
    1. John receives the email with the verification code.
    2. He enters the verification code on the Azure B2C page.
    3. Azure B2C verifies the code and authenticates John.
  5. Application Submission:
    1. John is redirected back to the Power Pages portal.
    2. He fills out the application form with the necessary details.
    3. John submits the application.
  6. Confirmation:
    1. John receives a confirmation message on the portal.
    2. An email confirmation is also sent to John’s email.

Technical User Journey:
  1. Portal Access and Redirection:
    1. The Power Pages portal is configured with Azure B2C for authentication.
    2. When John clicks "Submit Application," the portal triggers the Azure B2C authentication flow.
  2. Azure B2C Authentication Flow:
    1. Azure B2C policy is configured to use email as the identity provider.
    2. Azure B2C sends a verification code to the email provided by John.
  3. MFA Implementation:
    1. Azure B2C uses a built-in MFA policy to verify the code entered by John.
    2. Upon successful verification, Azure B2C issues a token.
  4. Token Handling and Redirection:
    1. The token is used to authenticate John and redirect him back to the Power Pages portal.
    2. The portal uses the token to establish John’s session.
  5. Form Submission:
    1. John fills out and submits the application form.
    2. The application data is stored in the backend database.
  6. Notification:
    1. The portal sends a confirmation email using a configured email service (e.g., SendGrid, Office 365).
    2. John receives the confirmation on the portal and via email.


Scenario 2: Submitting an Application for a Course via Power Pages Portal Using Azure B2C with Australia Digital Identity

User Journey:
  1. User Accesses Portal:
    1. Emily visits the Power Pages portal to apply for a course.
    2. She clicks on "Submit Application."
  2. Sign-in Process:
    1. Emily is prompted to sign in using her Australia Digital Identity.
    2. The portal redirects Emily to the Azure B2C login page.
  3. Australia Digital Identity Authentication:
    1. Emily selects "Australia Digital Identity" as the login method.
    2. Azure B2C redirects Emily to the Service Australia login page.
  4. Digital Identity Verification:
    1. Emily logs in using her Service Australia credentials.
    2. Service Australia verifies Emily’s identity and sends claims back to Azure B2C.
  5. Application Submission:
    1. Emily is redirected back to the Power Pages portal.
    2. Her identity information is pre-filled in the application form based on the claims.
    3. Emily completes any additional required fields and submits the application.
  6. Confirmation:
    1. Emily receives a confirmation message on the portal.
    2. An email confirmation is also sent to Emily’s email.

Technical User Journey:
  1. Portal Access and Redirection:
    1. The Power Pages portal is configured with Azure B2C for authentication.
    2. When Emily clicks "Submit Application," the portal triggers the Azure B2C authentication flow.
  2. Azure B2C Authentication Flow:
    1. Azure B2C policy is configured with a custom policy to integrate with Service Australia’s Digital Identity.
    2. Emily selects "Australia Digital Identity" and is redirected to Service Australia.
  3. Service Australia Authentication:
    1. Azure B2C custom policy triggers the OpenAPI of Service Australia for authentication.
    2. Emily logs in using her Service Australia credentials.
    3. Service Australia verifies the identity and returns claims (such as name, email, and other attributes) to Azure B2C.
  4. Token Handling and Redirection:
    1. Azure B2C processes the claims and issues a token.
    2. Emily is authenticated and redirected back to the Power Pages portal.
  5. Form Pre-Fill and Submission:
    1. The portal uses the claims to pre-fill Emily’s identity information in the application form.
    2. Emily completes and submits the form.
    3. The application data is stored in the backend database.
  6. Notification:
    1. The portal sends a confirmation email using a configured email service (e.g., SendGrid, Office 365).
    2. Emily receives the confirmation on the portal and via email.

Title: Architecture: Implement Genesys Integration in Microsoft Dynamics 365 CE
Description:
Objective:
To integrate Genesys, a customer experience and contact centre platform, with Microsoft Dynamics 365 Customer Engagement (CE). This integration aims to enhance customer interactions by leveraging Genesys's capabilities within the Dynamics 365 environment, enabling a seamless, unified customer service experience.

High-Level Architecture:
  1. Genesys Cloud: The primary platform for customer interactions, including voice, chat, email, and social media.
  2. Dynamics 365 CE: The CRM system where customer information, cases, and interactions are managed.
  3. Integration Layer: Middleware or APIs facilitating communication between Genesys and Dynamics 365 CE.
Acceptance Criteria:
Acceptance Criteria:

1. Integration Completeness: 
  • All identified use cases are successfully implemented and tested.
  • Data synchronization between Genesys and Dynamics 365 CE is accurate and timely.
2. Performance:
  • The integration does not introduce significant latency or performance degradation in either system.
  • Real-time interactions are accurately reflected in Dynamics 365 CE.
3. Security:
  • Data exchanged between Genesys and Dynamics 365 CE is secure and compliant with relevant regulations.
  • Only authorized users can access the integrated features.
4. User Experience:
  • Users can seamlessly view and manage customer interactions from Genesys within Dynamics 365 CE.
  • Custom workflows and UI enhancements meet user requirements and improve efficiency.
5. Documentation:
  • Comprehensive documentation is provided for both technical and non-technical users.

Title: Architecture: AI and Copilot Solutions in Dynamics 365 and Power Apps
Description:
Overview:
This feature aims to explore and implement different AI and Copilot solutions across different modules and functionalities within Dynamics 365 and Power Apps. These solutions will leverage artificial intelligence, machine learning, and collaborative tools to automate tasks, provide insights, and assist users in performing their daily activities more efficiently.
Acceptance Criteria:
1. Each solution should be evaluated based on its effectiveness in achieving the intended objectives.
  2. Integration with Dynamics 365 and Power Apps should be seamless, with minimal disruption to existing workflows.
  3. User feedback and performance metrics should be continuously monitored to refine and improve the implemented solutions.
  4. Comprehensive documentation and training materials should be provided to users to ensure adoption and proficiency.

************************************
Below are the some of the initiative solutions can be consider with business

1. Chatbot for Customer Support:
As a customer service representative, I want to deploy a chatbot integrated with Dynamics 365 to handle common customer inquiries and provide instant responses.

2. AI-Powered Knowledge Management:
As a support person, I want to use AI to organize and retrieve knowledge articles, FAQs, and troubleshooting guides to assist customers more efficiently.

3. Co-piloted Business Process Automation:
As a product owner, I want to automate repetitive tasks and workflows by collaborating with an AI-powered co-pilot to design and optimize business processes.

4. Intelligent Document Processing:
As a product owner, I want to automate document processing tasks such as data extraction, classification, and validation using AI-powered OCR and NLP techniques.

5. Sentiment Analysis for Feedback:
As a member from leadership team, I want to analyse feedback and social media interactions using sentiment analysis to understand overall.

Title: Document risk treatments to whitelist PS tenant
Description:
Risks

  • A lack of understanding regarding data management poses a risk to the department and may lead to a data breach and reputational damage as PS lacks sufficient security documentation.
  • Azure B2C can store user data such as personal information, login credentials, and payment details, any security breach can lead to unauthorised access to this information, resulting in departmental reputational damage, loss of stakeholder confidence and possible financial loss.
  • Using DEWR managed accounts is not recommended as ASQA is intending to leverage the M365 component of the PS tenant. This can lead to unauthorised access from an external actor as the tenancy is outside of the internal network.
  • Developers can bypass copy/paste controls enforced. This may result in corporate data/information being processed and/or stored outside of enterprise controls.
Acceptance Criteria:
Treatments

  • Assess the use of a VDI solution, such as W365 or AVD. To allow accounts provided for PS to be used and assist in maintaining a clear delineation between the users ASQA data and their PS data. - PK
    • If a VDI solution is used, develop a Standard Operating Procedure outlining the log in process for ASQA users. Ensure passwords used to access the VDI are different from Departmental login details. Also, engage with Cyber Operations to keep a log of users accessing the VDI and ensure provisions are in place to archive the logs.
  • Relevant DEWR and ASQA teams to ensure appropriate network and encryption protections are in place. - PK
  • ASQA Digital Transformation Technical Lead with assistance from relevant DEWR teams to develop a high-level diagram that shows the architecture of the PS tenant, Azure Services and DEWR tenancy. -  PK
  • ASQA Digital Transformation Technical Lead to provide Cyber Assurance with a Privacy Threshold Assessment (PTA) for Level up for Dynamics 365. - JKS

ASQA will be responsible for liaising with the Gateway, Technology Architecture, and Azure Services teams to ensure the security decision is implemented smoothly in consultation with the DEWR Cyber Teams.

Title: Unplanned: Build a POC solution to update mobilephone and telephone1 in ARMS
Description:
Hi All,

 

This meeting is to discuss Genesys and data within asqanet/ARMS for contact phone numbers and Genesys integration.

 

Now, with an incoming call via Genesys, if the contact has a +61432… it won’t show to select, but if it is recorded as +610432, it will show with the ‘0’ included. And if it is an outbound call, the number won’t dial with a +610432, you need to remove the ‘0’ before making the phone call. We will need to contact Genesys to get the ‘0’ removed for this to work both of incoming/outgoing calls.

 

There also needs to be considerations made regarding the current data within asqanet/ARMS. Currently it is not showing the area code for landline numbers/mobile numbers.  

 

And any new data coming in asks for the area codes (do we just fix ARMS data/ collecting from new portal/processes for TPA/CEMS when they create the contact within ARMS), and any internal There also needs be a data cleanse for landline numbers as well if we are addressing the mobile numbers (07,02,03 etc).

 

There needs to be decisions made on this quite quickly for the Genesys release.

Title: Dataflows - DEVINT: Implement new phone number formatting for mobile numbers.
Description:
Mobile/mobilephone 14 if mobile number has 11 digits, and the first two digits are '61' then add '+' in front of the number
15 if mobile number has 6 digits, and the first two digits are '13' then add '+61' in front of the number
16 if mobile number has 10 digits, and the first 4 digits either '1800' or '1300' then add '+61' in front of the number
17 if mobile number has 10 digits, and the first 2 digits are either '04', '03','02','07' or '08' then remove '0' and add '+61' in front of the number
ELSE cleanup: remove spaces, hyphen and brackets '(', ')'
Acceptance Criteria: New mobile number format is implemented in ARMS.

Title: Dataflows - DEVINT: Implement new phone number formatting for landline numbers.
Description:
Landline/telephone1 1 if landline number has 11 digits, and the first two digits are '61' then add '+' in front of the number
2 if landline number has 6 digits, and the first two digits are '13' then add '+61' in front of the number
3 if landline number has 10 digits, and the first 4 digits are '1800' or '1300' then add '+61' in front of the number
4 if landline number has 10 digits, and the first 2 digits are either '04', '03','02','07' or '08' then remove '0' and add '+61' in  front of the number
5 if landline number has 8 digits, and the state of the physical address is VIC/VICTORIA then add '+613' in  front of the number
6 if landline number has 8 digits, and the state of the physical address is TAS/TASMANIA then add '+613' in  front of the number
7 if landline number has 8 digits, and the state of the physical address is ACT/AUSTRALIAN CAPITAL TERRITORY then add '+612' in front of the number
8 if landline number has 8 digits, and the state of the physical address is NSW/NEW SOUTH WALES then add '+612' in front of the number
9 if landline number has 8 digits, and the state of the physical address is QLD/QUEENSLAND then add '+617' in front of the number
10 if landline number has 8 digits, and the state of the physical address is NT/NORTHERN TERRITORY then add '+618' in front of the number
11 if landline number has 8 digits, and the state of the physical address is SA/SOUTH AUSTRALIA then add '+618' in front of the number
12 if landline number has 8 digits, and the state of the physical address is WA/WESTERN AUSTRALIA then add '+618' in front of the number
13 if landline number has 9 digits, and the first digit is either '2','3','7' or'8', then ???
Acceptance Criteria: New landline number format is implemented in ARMS.

Title: Add new cores to Prod BI Server
Description:
There are two issues we have been facing:

 

  1. ASQA ETL job failed unexpectedly due to unplanned server reboot (happened a few times since August 2024). It takes a day to resolve and longer if the job failed on the weekend.
  2. ASQA ETL job takes longer to complete and therefore has flow on impact on timely reporting

 

DEWR have provided a few suggestions with respect to (1) above.

 

  1. Increase the number of cores to the CPU to help avoid CPU being maxed out, and thus avoid sudden server reboot and that means, not stopping ASQA ETL job from executing.
  2. Optimise ASQA ETL code - given the workload and resource constraints, we have not gone down this path as it can take a fair bit of time. I don’t have a view of how long this might take

Implement Student Signup Prototype
Description:
Complete end to end functional prototype that includes
  • Sinning up by clicking a link that lands the user in Azure B2C signup first
    • Azure AD signup will verify email, identify user as a student using URN and DOB, allow set a password, creates a B2C account with a ASQA customer id
    • Rejects re-signup using same URN and DOB
  • Then lands on the QI form with enough information to load RTOs and Quals for the student
  • Student can sign in again to the QI form

Title: Design Establish Connectivity Between B2C and Internal Logic App
Description:
Student signup in Azure B2C needs to identify user as a valid student.

This can be done by Azure B2C calling HTTP trigger in a Logic App to validate student URN and DOB.

Logic app used is in a VNET, therefore the B2C can't connect to the Logic App directly.

Is it possible to make a call to an azure app service inside a vnet from azure ad b2c ? - Microsoft Q&A

In general check whether there is an already an established ASQA pattern to expose an internal resource. If not establish a new pattern.

Important points to consider
  • Protection from common web exploits and malicious traffic 
  • Fine-grained security 
  • Rate limiting
  • DDoS protection
  • Load balancing
  • DR and high availability

Title: Authenticate B2C to Web API and Web API to Dataverse
Description:
Student signup in Azure B2C needs to identify user as a valid student.

This can be done by Azure B2C calling HTTP endpoint of a Web API to validate student ARN and DOB against Dataverse.

To achieve the above Azure B2C needs to needs to authenticate to the Web API

Web API app registration and API permissions - Microsoft identity platform | Microsoft Learn

To achieve the above Web API needs to needs to authenticate to Dataverse. Therefore a App Registration with a secret and access to Dataverse is required - DONE

Title: Linking B2C and Dynamics Contact
Description:
After student signs up, a link between the Azure B2C account and the Contact in Dynamics needs to be created for the following reasons.
  • Portal needs to retrieve the students RTOs and Quals after signup and during subsequent logins
  • Stop re-signup already signed up students
  • Allow student to change the primary email and the sign in email 
Scope of this task is to finalize a solution and include in the prototype

Kind Regards,

Copy of files from blob to SharePoint after max 15 files upload
Description:
At the moment every time user updates the submission file copying solution deletes the submitted files and re-copies the files to SharePoint. For example, if a user submitted 5 files and then updates the submission with another 5, then the total files copied to SharePoint is 15 files. Another example is if the user submits 15 files and keep updating the response (not adding new files due to allowed 15 files are already uploaded), then the file copying solution keeps re-copying the file.

This could lead to performance issues in Logic App, SharePoint and network bandwidth.

When the maximum of 15 files has been uploaded and copied to SharePoint, the trigger of the logic apps should not re-copy the files to SharePoint.
